        <div class="eyebrow">09 &middot; Insurance agent partner FAQs</div>
        <h2>Questions Florida buyers, homeowners, and agents ask, answered.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-cross-links" style="margin-bottom: var(--s-10); padding: var(--s-6); background: var(--paper-warm); border-left: 3px solid var(--blue);">
          <p style="margin: 0 0 var(--s-3) 0; font-family: var(--serif); font-size: var(--text-md); font-weight: 500;">More <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">insurance partnership and borrower-side</a> resources at Stairway</p>
          <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: var(--s-5); font-size: var(--text-sm); line-height: 1.7; list-style: none;">
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/jumbo-loan/">Jumbo loan details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-investor-loan/">DSCR Non-QM details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/condo-loan/">Condo loan details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/">100+ mortgage calculators</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/">Start your pre-approval</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What&rsquo;s the difference between HO-3, HO-5, and HO-6 policies?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">HO-3 is the standard homeowners policy with named-perils personal property + all-risk dwelling coverage. HO-5 is the premier variant with all-risk on both dwelling AND personal property (broader). HO-6 is the condo unit-owner policy covering walls-in interior + personal property + liability + loss assessment. Agent selection depends on property type + coverage preference.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Do I need NFIP flood insurance in Florida?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Required by mortgage lender in FEMA-designated <a href="https://www.fema.gov/flood-maps" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Special Flood Hazard Areas (SFHA)</a> (high-risk flood zones). Optional but recommended in X zones for many Florida properties given hurricane storm surge risk. NFIP maximum: $250K dwelling + $100K contents. Private flood emerging with higher limits available.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What is Citizens Property Insurance and when does it apply?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Citizens Property Insurance Corporation is Florida&rsquo;s state-backed nonprofit insurer of last resort. Available when private market quote exceeds Citizens by a defined margin. Coverage limits and underwriting rules differ from private market. Depopulation initiatives transfer policies to private carriers when market conditions allow.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the hurricane deductible work?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Florida hurricane deductible structured as percentage of dwelling coverage (commonly 2%, 5%, or 10%) separate from all-other-perils deductible. For $500K dwelling at 5%: $25,000 hurricane deductible vs $1,000-$5,000 standard deductible. Triggered by National Hurricane Center named-storm declaration. Applies once per calendar year for named storms per Florida Statutes Chapter 627.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What is a wind mitigation inspection and is it worth doing?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Florida-specific inspection identifying premium-discount features: hip roof shape, roof deck attachment, roof-to-wall connections (clips / single / double straps), opening protection (impact-rated windows / shutters), secondary water resistance, roof covering compliance. Discounts can be substantial; cost typically $75-$150 with potential annual premium savings of $500-$2,000+ depending on property.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do older Florida homes need a Four-Point Inspection?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Carriers typically require Four-Point Inspection for properties 25-30+ years old: roof, electrical, plumbing, HVAC condition assessment. Cost $75-$150. Identifies any major system issues affecting insurability. Some carriers require updated electrical (no aluminum wiring), updated plumbing (no polybutylene), or roof under certain age.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What is loss assessment coverage and why do I need it for a condo?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Loss assessment coverage in condo HO-6 covers special assessments from the condo association master policy gaps (deductible, exclusions, limits exceeded). Critical post-Surfside (June 2021) and Florida SB 4-D milestone inspection + reserve funding requirements. Typical $5K-$50K coverage; agents recommend higher limits given recent special assessment trends.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When do I need surplus lines insurance?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Surplus lines (non-admitted E&amp;S carriers) covers risks the admitted market won&rsquo;t take: older homes, coastal exposure, prior claims history, properties exceeding admitted carrier underwriting appetite. Higher premiums typical but broader underwriting reach. Florida Surplus Lines Service Office coordinates market regulation. Agent must hold surplus lines license endorsement.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How much homeowners insurance do I need for my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Lender requires dwelling coverage at or above replacement cost (not market value). 12 months premium prepaid at closing plus initial escrow reserve typically 2-3 months. Mortgagee clause naming the lender + loan number. Binder issued at closing as proof of coverage; full policy follows post-closing. Coverage maintained through ownership for lender protection.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m an insurance agent. Can Stairway help with my own home mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; for agency principals and producers with W-2 + commission + book-of-business renewals + bonus + variable comp, Stairway handles multi-source qualifying with Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 variable income synthesis. Independent agency owners with K-1 partnership income use B3-3.4-02 partnership documentation. See our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/professional-services/">professional services hub</a> for multi-source income qualifying paths.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

